PROCEDURE:   Gated SPECT Myocardial Perfusion Study.  CLINICAL INDICATION:    Patient with chest pain and history of past STEMI. Study is performed to detect possible stress-induced myocardial ischemia.  TECHNIQUE: Multiple planar and tomographic images of the left ventricle were obtained 30 minutes post injection of 13.9 mCi Tc-99m tetrofosmin.  The patient was then transported to the cardiology laboratory and infused with 0.4 mg of Regadenoson which was followed with an injection of 24.55 mCi Tc-99m tetrofosmin. 1 minute postinfusion patient became hypotensive with blood pressures 80's/60's with bradycardia into the 40's and became unresponsive. 50 mg of Aminophylline administered for symptoms and within 1 minute of onset heart rate and blood pressure returned near baseline and patient became responsive. Patient was monitored for an additional 20 minutes and remained stable. Patient returned to the nuclear medicine laboratory for planar and SPECT imaging of the left ventricle.  Both rest and post pharmacologic stress images were compared.  COMPARISON: None  FINDINGS OF MYOCARDIAL PERFUSION IMAGES:  LEFT VENTRICULAR CHAMBER SIZE:  Normal  PERFUSION REST AND STRESS :           LV:                           No abnormal tracer uptake. Mild decreased tracer uptake in the inferior wall, with similar pattern on both rest and stress images, nearly completely reversed on attenuation corrected images, consistent with diaphragmatic attenuation artifact. Mild decreased tracer uptake in apical region on both rest and stress images, is consistent with physiological apical thinning.  GATED STUDY:  Done 30 minutes post stress  Demonstrates mild dyskinetic wall motion  LV EJECTION FRACTION:  50-55% on visual assessment  IMPRESSION: 1. No evidence of stress induced ischemia. 2. Normal left ventricular chamber size with mild dyskinetic wall motion. 3. Normal LVEF 50-55% on visual assessment.  NOTE:  EKG interpretation can be found under Exercise/Stress Procedure notes.     This study was reviewed and interpreted with Dr. Lu and dictated by Dr. Michael Kim.

INCIDENTAL CT FINDINGS:   None.  IMPRESSION:  1. Nondiagnostic PET/CT for cardiac sarcoidosis given patient noncompliance with sarcoid diet prior to the performance of the study, which was confirmed upon direct inquiry. 2. PROCEDURE_NAME: STRESS TEST, REGADENOSON W MYOCARDIAL PERFUSION SPECT (MULTI STUDY)
PROCEDURE_REPORT: PROCEDURE:   Gated SPECT Myocardial Perfusion Study.  CLINICAL INDICATION:    Hypertension. Chest pain.. Study is performed to detect possible stress-induced myocardial ischemia.  TECHNIQUE: Multiple planar and tomographic images of the left ventricle were obtained 30 minutes post injection of 13.07 mCi Tc-99m tetrofosmin.  The patient was then transported to the cardiology laboratory and infused with 0.4 mg of Regadenoson which was followed with an injection of 25.60 mCi Tc-99m tetrofosmin.  The patient tolerated the procedure well and returned to the nuclear medicine laboratory for planar and SPECT imaging of the left ventricle.  Both rest and post pharmacologic stress images were compared.  COMPARISON: None  FINDINGS OF MYOCARDIAL PERFUSION IMAGES:  LEFT VENTRICULAR CHAMBER SIZE:  Normal  PERFUSION REST AND STRESS :  The study is limited by bowel activity abutting the inferoseptal wall. The bowel activity is changing the intensity of the left ventricle. Although there is apparent more intense activity in the septum compared to the lateral wall which is seen on both the attenuated and none attenuated corrected images but more pronounced on the none attenuated corrected. The difference is more likely due to the artifact from the bowel activity rather than true          LV:                           There is an area of decreased counts seen in the very distal anterior wall and apex on the stress images but it is minimally improved on rest however the adjacent area on rest is worse than stress. Overall, this is felt to be due to an artifact. This area also has better appearance on the none attenuated corrected images on stress. Overall, this is believed to be due to an artifact rather than very subtle ischemia. The difference in the lateral wall as described above likely due to an artifact from bowel.  . In the distal anterior wall and apex, the some distress score and summed difference score is 0.    GATED STUDY:  Done 30 minutes post stress  Demonstrates normal wall motion   LV EJECTION FRACTION:  54%.

PROCEDURE:   Gated SPECT Myocardial Perfusion Study.  CLINICAL INDICATION:  65-year-old gentleman with chest pain. Study is performed to detect possible stress-induced myocardial ischemia.  TECHNIQUE: Multiple planar and tomographic images of the left ventricle were obtained 30 minutes post injection of 11.975 mCi Tc-99m tetrofosmin.  The patient was then transported to the cardiology laboratory and infused with 0.4 mg of Regadenoson which was followed with an injection of 26.046 mCi Tc-99m tetrofosmin.  The patient tolerated the procedure well and returned to the nuclear medicine laboratory for planar and SPECT imaging of the left ventricle.  Both rest and post pharmacologic stress images were compared.  COMPARISON: None available.  FINDINGS OF MYOCARDIAL PERFUSION IMAGES:  LEFT VENTRICULAR CHAMBER SIZE:  Normal.  PERFUSION REST AND STRESS :           LV:                           No full-thickness left ventricular perfusion defect identified. Mild decreased tracer uptake in the inferior wall, with similar pattern on both rest and stress images, nearly completely reversed on attenuation corrected images, consistent with diaphragmatic attenuation artifact.  GATED STUDY:  Done 30 minutes post stress demonstrates normal wall motion.  LV EJECTION FRACTION:  49%  _______________________ IMPRESSION: 1. No evidence of stress induced ischemia. 2. Normal left ventricular chamber size with normal wall motion. 3. Left ventricular ejection fraction calculated at 49%.  NOTE:  EKG interpretation can be found under Exercise/Stress Procedure notes.   This study was reviewed and interpreted by radiology attending Dr. Anderson with dictation by radiology resident Dr. Allen.

PROCEDURE_REPORT: PROCEDURE:   Gated SPECT Myocardial Perfusion Study.  CLINICAL INDICATION:    57-year-old female with chest pain. Study is performed to detect possible stress-induced myocardial ischemia.  TECHNIQUE: Multiple planar and tomographic images of the left ventricle were obtained 30 minutes post injection of 12.6 mCi Tc-99m tetrofosmin.  The patient was then transported to the cardiology laboratory and infused with 0.4 mg of Regadenoson which was followed with an injection of 26 mCi Tc-99m tetrofosmin.  The patient tolerated the procedure well and returned to the nuclear medicine laboratory for planar and SPECT imaging of the left ventricle.  Both rest and post pharmacologic stress images were compared.  COMPARISON: None  FINDINGS OF MYOCARDIAL PERFUSION IMAGES:  The study is limited by the intense bowel activity which is covering part of the inferior wall on both stress and rest with variable appearance resulting in changing the intensity of the whole left ventricle between the stress and rest images. The study was reprocessed multiple times in an attempt to indeterminate this artifact with no success.  LEFT VENTRICULAR CHAMBER SIZE:  Borderline normal  PERFUSION REST AND STRESS :           LV:                           There is apparent decreased activity along the anterior wall seen on the stress images. Although this activity appears to be improving on rest however the adjacent area is worse on rest than stress. This area is approximately 1-2 segments. Overall, this is an equivocal finding more likely to be due to an artifact and less likely due to a true findings however the evaluation is limited as described above..   The summed stress score equal 5, the summed rest score equals 1 and a summed difference score equal 4.  GATED STUDY:  Done 30 minutes post stress  Demonstrates borderline normal wall motion  LV EJECTION FRACTION:  Approximately 50% by visual estimation

PROCEDURE_REPORT: PROCEDURE:   Gated SPECT Myocardial Perfusion Study.  CLINICAL INDICATION:    History of hypertension, hyperlipidemia, and angina. Study is performed to detect possible stress-induced myocardial ischemia.  TECHNIQUE: Multiple planar and tomographic images of the left ventricle were obtained 30 minutes post injection of 12.3 mCi Tc-99m tetrofosmin.  The patient was then transported to the cardiology laboratory and infused with 0.4 mg of Regadenoson which was followed with an injection of 27.5 mCi Tc-99m tetrofosmin.  The patient tolerated the procedure well and returned to the nuclear medicine laboratory for planar and SPECT imaging of the left ventricle.  Both rest and post pharmacologic stress images were compared.  COMPARISON: None  FINDINGS OF MYOCARDIAL PERFUSION IMAGES:  LEFT VENTRICULAR CHAMBER SIZE:  Normal  PERFUSION REST AND STRESS :  The study is limited by the intense bowel activity obscuring the inferior wall and changing the intensity of the whole left ventricle on both stress and rest.          LV:                           No definite scintigraphic evidence for ischemia or infarction. There is apparent subtle to mild decreased activity along the anterior wall on the stress attenuated corrected images. However, this area is better on the non-attenuated corrected stress images. It is felt to be due to an artifact.   The summed stress score equal 1, the summed rest score equals 0 and a summed difference score equal 1.  GATED STUDY:  Done 30 minutes post stress  Demonstrates normal wall motion   LV EJECTION FRACTION:  66 %

PROCEDURE: PET/CT examination from base of skull to mid thigh level  CLINICAL STATEMENT: 63-year-old female with past medical history of atrial fibrillation/flutter, and moderate arthritis concern for possible cardiac sarcoid.  TECHNIQUE: 11.34 mCi of FDG was administered by IV injection into the right antecubital vein.  Approximately 61 minutes post injection, low-dose CT and PET images from the skull base to the upper thighs were acquired on the Discovery 690 PET/CT with the patient in the fasted state. The CT was with oral contrast, but without IV contrast and was used for image fusion, attenuation correction and lesion localization only.  This is not a diagnostic CT and a separate CT report will not be generated.  The patient's fasting blood glucose measured just before IV injection of FDG was 83 mg/dl.    The standardized uptake values (SUV) are normalized to patient body weight and indicate the highest activity concentration (SUVmax) in a given disease site.   COMPARISON FDG PET/CT: None available. PROCEDURE:   Gated SPECT Myocardial Perfusion Study.  CLINICAL INDICATION:       . Study is performed to detect possible stress-induced myocardial ischemia.  TECHNIQUE: Multiple planar and tomographic images of the left ventricle were obtained 30 minutes post injection of 12.1 mCi Tc-99m tetrofosmin.  The patient was then transported to the cardiology laboratory and infused with 0.4 mg of Regadenoson which was followed with an injection of 25.8 mCi Tc-99m tetrofosmin.  The patient tolerated the procedure well and returned to the nuclear medicine laboratory for planar and SPECT imaging of the left ventricle.  Both rest and post pharmacologic stress images were compared.  COMPARISON: None  FINDINGS OF MYOCARDIAL PERFUSION IMAGES:  LEFT VENTRICULAR CHAMBER SIZE:  Normal  PERFUSION REST AND STRESS :           LV: On the stress images, there is subtle decreased activity of the anterior wall compared to the remaining walls of the left ventricle. This area has normal appearance on the rest images. This area is predominantly evident in the midportion of the anterior wall. The findings described above may represent subtle reversible ischemia. However, due to body habitus and somewhat variable appearance on rest and artifact cannot be entirely excluded.  GATED STUDY:  Done 30 minutes post stress  Demonstrates normal wall motion   LV EJECTION FRACTION:  Approximately 65% by visual assessment.  IMPRESSION: 1. The findings described above in the midportion of the anterior wall may represent subtle reversible ischemia. However, due to patient's body habitus and the subtle difference between stress and rest, an artifact resulting in this appearance cannot be entirely excluded 2. Normal left ventricular chamber size and wall motion. 3. Normal LVEF approximately 65% by visual assessment.  NOTE:  EKG interpretation can be found under Exercise/Stress Procedure notes.

PROCEDURE:   Exercise Gated SPECT Myocardial Perfusion Study.  CLINICAL INDICATION:    Preoperative examination. History of cardiac arrhythmia.  Previous study:  None available.  TECHNIQUE: Multiple planar and tomographic images of the left ventricle were obtained 30 minutes post injection of 12.9 mCi Tc-99m tetrofosmin.  The patient was then transported to the cardiology laboratory and underwent a exercise stress test.  The patient achieved a predicted heart rate of  90 % of maximum, with estimated workload of 10.1 METS.  The cardiac stress was judged to be adequate.  One minute before completing the exercise,  an injection of 25.6 mCi Tc-99m tetrofosmin was given.  The patient tolerated the procedure well and returned to the nuclear medicine laboratory for planar and SPECT imaging of the left ventricle.  Both rest and post stress images were compared.  FINDINGS OF MYOCARDIAL PERFUSION IMAGES:  LEFT VENTRICULAR CHAMBER SIZE:  Dilated.  PERFUSION REST AND STRESS :           LV:                           No abnormal tracer uptake.     GATED STUDY:  Done 30 minutes post stress demonstrates left ventricular dilatation and global hypokinesis.  LV EJECTION FRACTION:  30%  IMPRESSION: 1.  No evidence of stress induced ischemia. 2.  Global hypokinesis with decreased LVEF of 30%  NOTE:  EKG interpretation can be found under Exercise/Stress Procedure notes.     This study was reviewed and interpreted by Dr. Anderson prior to final dictation by Dr. B. McDowell.

PROCEDURE:   Gated SPECT Myocardial Perfusion Study.  CLINICAL INDICATION:    Chest pain. Study is performed to detect possible stress-induced myocardial ischemia.  TECHNIQUE: Multiple planar and tomographic images of the left ventricle were obtained 30 minutes post injection of 12.4 mCi Tc-99m tetrofosmin.  The patient was then transported to the cardiology laboratory and infused with 0.4 mg of Regadenoson which was followed with an injection of 25.8 mCi Tc-99m tetrofosmin.  The patient tolerated the procedure well and returned to the nuclear medicine laboratory for planar and SPECT imaging of the left ventricle.  Both rest and post pharmacologic stress images were compared.  COMPARISON: None  FINDINGS OF MYOCARDIAL PERFUSION IMAGES:  LEFT VENTRICULAR CHAMBER SIZE:  Normal  PERFUSION REST AND STRESS :           LV:                           There is no scintigraphic evidence for ischemia or infarction. Some variable appearance seen within the anterior wall which is variable appearance on rest and consistent with artifact.. Mild decreased tracer uptake in the inferior wall, with similar pattern on both rest and stress images, nearly completely reversed on attenuation corrected images, consistent with diaphragmatic attenuation artifact.  The summed stress score equals 1, the summed rest score equals 0 and a summed difference score equals 1.  GATED STUDY:  Done 30 minutes post stress  Demonstrates normal wall motion   LV EJECTION FRACTION:  Approximately 50-55% by visual estimation.  IMPRESSION: 1. No definite scintigraphic evidence of stress induced ischemia. 2. Normal left ventricular chamber size and wall motion. 3. Normal LVEF approximately 50-55% by visual estimation.  NOTE:  EKG interpretation can be found under Exercise/Stress Procedure notes.
